# Task 1 – Project Report: Digital Literacy Infographic

## Tool Used
For this task, I used **HTML/CSS** (rendered in a browser) as my design tool, which functions similarly to Canva in that it lets you create fully visual, styled one-page layouts — but with complete creative control over typography, color, and composition.

## What the Design Shows
The infographic covers five core areas of Digital Literacy. At the top, a bold definition explains what digital literacy means beyond just "using gadgets." A statistics bar highlights key global data — such as 92% of jobs requiring digital skills — to show why it matters. The main section is split into three cards covering **Safe Internet Practices** (with pill-styled safety tips), **Useful Digital Tools for Students** (tools like Notion, Google Scholar, Canva, and Zoom), and two further cards on **Email Etiquette** (with a step-by-step checklist) and **Professional Online Presence** (numbered action steps for building a digital identity).

## One Thing I Found Interesting
The most interesting challenge was making the layout visually engaging without becoming cluttered. Balancing five different topics on a single page meant every element — font size, color accent, spacing — had to carry its weight. Using a consistent color-coded accent bar on each card helped group information clearly while keeping the design lively and readable at a glance.

